    "body": "### Problem\n\nUsing `vim.opt.diffopt:append('inline:word')` produces a different result than running `:set diffopt+=inline:word`. The vimscript variant removes `inline:char` from the setting before appending `inline:word`. The lua variant just appends `inline:word`.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnvim --clean\n:set diffopt?\n  --> diffopt=internal,filler,closeoff,indent-heuristic,inline:char,linematch:40\n:lua vim.opt.diffopt:append('inline:word')\n  --> diffopt=internal,filler,closeoff,indent-heuristic,inline:char,linematch:40,inline:word\n:set diffopt?\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`inline:char` gets removed and replaced with `inline:word`\n\nWhy I expected this: help for `vim.opt:append()` says to look at help for `:set+=`. Help for `:set+=` describes this behavior. Finally this is what happens when I use the vimscript equivalent:\n\n```\nnvim --clean\n:set diffopt?\n  --> diffopt=internal,filler,closeoff,indent-heuristic,inline:char,linematch:40\n:set diffopt+=inline:word\n:set diffopt?\n  --> diffopt=internal,filler,closeoff,indent-heuristic,linematch:40,inline:word\n```\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.13.0-dev-172+g7bb8231577\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, this is a lua problem\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu 24.04\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nkitty 0.46.2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nbob",
